Seed Pod Wind Dispersal of Holmgrenâ€™s Milk-vetch, Astragalus holmgreniorum

Sydney Houghton

4/26/2018

Introduction

Astragalus holmgreniorum is an endangered endemic perennial herb of the Northern Mojave Desert near St.Â George, UT. The morphological characteristics of the leguminous pods at the stage they begin to loose seeds exhibits aerodynamic qualities. This study was performed to determine if wind dispersal is possible and what distance will pods potentially move.

Procedure

A runway was designed with different substrates: sand, small gravel, and medium gravel. Three degrees of slope were tested: no slope, upslope and downslope. Three speeds of wind (4.3 m/s, 7.1 m/s, 10.7 m/s) were provided by a fan to mimic habitat and environmental conditions in a controlled laboratory setting. For each treatment combination a new group of pods was tested totaling 324 individuals each trialed at two orientations to the wind. Each pod was timed from the start of the fan to the first stop of movement. Pods were given an equal cut off time if no movement occured.

Data Analysis

Of the 324 trials 89% of pods moved a distance and stopped within 15 seconds of wind exposure and 57% travled to 152.4 cm or more. Runway maximum length is 304.8 cm, roughly 3 meters.

The plot below demonstrates the amount of pods that did not leave the starting point and the pods that made it to the end of the runway.

The effect of wind on pod movement was evident during trials. But knowing that over 50% of our selection from the population moved a good distance in a short time is confirmation of wind as a dispersal component.

Conclusion/Acknowledgements

This investigation fills knowledge gaps in dispersal processes and provides valuable information for conservation efforts of this federally listed endangered species.
